  "response": "Microwave ovens do not cause cancer. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\n1. How microwaves work:\n- Microwaves use non-ionizing radiation to heat food\n- They cause water molecules to vibrate, generating heat\n- This type of radiation does not damage DNA or cause cellular mutations\n\n2. Scientific consensus:\n- Extensive research has found no link between microwave ovens and cancer\n- Microwaves do not emit harmful radiation like X-rays or gamma rays\n- The radiation is contained within the oven and does not penetrate human tissue\n\n3. Safety factors:\n- Microwave ovens have protective shields that prevent radiation leakage\n- Modern ovens have multiple safety mechanisms\n- Regulatory agencies like the FDA set strict safety standards for microwave ovens\n\n4. Important cautions:\n- Always use microwave-safe containers\n- Ensure your microwave is in good condition without damage\n- Follow manufacturer's instructions\n\n5. Key point:\nThe type of radiation used in microwave ovens is non-ionizing and does not have enough energy to cause cancer-causing DNA damage.\n\nWhile microwaves are safe, it's always good to use them as directed and maintain your appliance properly.",
